        <p>The most damaging belief in this demographic is that the plateau is age. That things slow down after 50 and that's just how it is. That the gap between effort and results is the inevitable cost of getting older.</p>
        <p>The research doesn't support that conclusion. What the research shows is that men over 50 who consume adequate protein and perform regular resistance training preserve significantly more muscle mass than those who don't — regardless of age. The biology is harder at 55 than at 35. It's not impossible. It's not even close to impossible.</p>
        <p>The men who are strong and capable at 65 and 70 aren't genetic outliers. They're men who figured out — earlier or later — that the gap between their results and their effort was a protein gap. A visibility gap. Not an age gap.</p>
